<h3>PYQ</h3>
<ol>
<li>for small farmer = poor acceptability reason + role in socio-economic upliftment (2017)</li>
<li>Supermarkets in Supply chain - fruits,&nbsp;vegetables (2018)</li>
<li>GoI steps for food processing (2019)</li>
<li>food processing - challenges, opportunities + role in farmer income (2020)</li></ol>
<h3>FPI in India : INTRO</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Industry size 30x</strong> since 1991 (now USD 300 bn)</li>
<li>&lt;10% of total agri produce is processed (USA - 65%, china 25%)</li>
<li>is fifth largest sector of the country's economy</li>
<li>11% employment provides</li>
<li><span style="color:#2ecc71"><em><strong>FPI in India is a sunrise sector changing the trend from sustenance to market-oriented that has gained prominence in recent years.</strong></em></span></li>
<li><span style="color:#16a085">10%</span> of total exports are processed food&nbsp;</li></ul>
<h3>Drivers of food processing (FP) :&nbsp;</h3>
<ul>
<li>Flourishing food production -<strong>&nbsp;300&nbsp;metric ton</strong>&nbsp;, highest</li>
<li>Reduce post harvest loss -&nbsp;NITI Ayog also estimates post-harvest losses close to <em><strong>Rs 90,000 crore.</strong></em></li>
<li>shelf life up&nbsp;</li>
<li>changing consumption behaviour of the user -
<ul>
<li>urbanisation - 50mn people (33% urban)</li>
<li>can nudge to millets via branding like 'nutri cereals'</li></ul></li>
<li>RTE, RTC (ready to eat n cook)&nbsp;</li></ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h4>GoI Steps</h4>
<ol>
<li>SAMAPDA yojana = modern infra</li>
<li>PMFME = formalisation&nbsp;</li>
<li>PLI for FPI</li>
<li>100% FDI&nbsp;</li>
<li>top to total = 50% subsidy on transport&nbsp;</li>
<li>draft national food processing policy 2019</li></ol>
